---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Types of Baijiu: Sauce, Strong, Light, and Rice Aroma';
const description = 'A practical guide to the main baijiu aroma types and how each style tastes, drinks, and fits different occasions.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <header class="article-header">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Aroma Types</p>
      <h1>Types of Baijiu</h1>
      <p class="lede">Aroma type is the most useful map for baijiu. It tells you more than bottle color, box design, or alcohol strength.</p>
    </div>
  </header>
  <section class="content">
    <article>
      <p>Baijiu is not one flavor. The category is organized by aroma type, and each type gives a different first impression. If a first-time drinker says "baijiu tastes harsh," the real question is often: which aroma type, which bottle, and in what setting?</p>

      <h2>Aroma Type Comparison</h2>
      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table>
          <thead><tr><th>Aroma type</th><th>Typical impression</th><th>Beginner difficulty</th><th>Best use case</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Sauce aroma</td><td>Savory, fermented, roasted grain, nutty, herbal, soy-like</td><td>Higher</td><td>Prestige gifting, slow tasting, serious reference bottles</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Strong aroma</td><td>Fruit, cellar, ripe grain, lush sweetness, expressive finish</td><td>Medium</td><td>Banquets, food pairing, approachable full-flavor tasting</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Light aroma</td><td>Clean grain, sharp lift, dry finish, less heavy fermentation</td><td>Lower to medium</td><td>First comparisons, clearer drinking, structured meals</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Rice aroma</td><td>Soft, mild, rice-like, sometimes floral or lightly sweet</td><td>Lower</td><td>Gentle introductions, cocktails, lower-intensity occasions</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h2>Sauce Aroma</h2>
      <p>Sauce-aroma baijiu is famous because of Maotai, but fame can mislead beginners. Good sauce aroma can be layered and memorable: roasted grain, savory fermentation, nuts, herbs, dried fruit, and a long finish. It can also feel demanding if you expect a clean, neutral spirit.</p>
      <p>Use sauce aroma when the occasion values prestige, cultural reference, or slow tasting. Do not use it as the default first bottle for a casual drinker unless they already like intense fermented flavors such as mezcal, funky rum, peated whisky, aged sherry, or savory spirits.</p>

      <h2>Strong Aroma</h2>
      <p>Strong aroma is one of the most important everyday styles in China. It can feel generous: fruit, cellar notes, grain sweetness, and a broad aroma that works well with rich meals. For many global drinkers, a good strong-aroma bottle is easier to understand than sauce aroma because the fruit and texture give the palate something familiar.</p>

      <h2>Light Aroma</h2>
      <p>Light aroma is cleaner and more direct. It can show grain, dryness, heat, and a sharper finish. The word "light" does not mean weak; it means the aroma profile is less dense than sauce or strong aroma. It is useful for drinkers who want structure before complexity.</p>

      <h2>Rice Aroma</h2>
      <p>Rice aroma is usually softer and less confrontational. It can be a good bridge for cocktails, tasting flights, and drinkers who are not ready for heavy fermented notes. The tradeoff is that it may not deliver the prestige or intensity many people associate with baijiu gifting.</p>

      <div class="callout">Practical rule: choose sauce aroma for prestige, strong aroma for expressive meals, light aroma for clearer structure, and rice aroma for softer entry points or cocktails.</div>

      <section class="faq">
        <h2>FAQ</h2>
        <h3>Which aroma type is best for beginners?</h3>
        <p>Light aroma, rice aroma, or an approachable strong-aroma bottle are usually safer than jumping directly into high-proof sauce aroma.</p>
        <h3>Is Maotai the same as baijiu?</h3>
        <p>No. Maotai is the most famous sauce-aroma brand, but baijiu includes many aroma types, regions, price levels, and drinking occasions.</p>
        <h3>Can aroma type predict quality?</h3>
        <p>No. Aroma type predicts style, not quality. There are excellent and poor examples inside every aroma type.</p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
